\begin_layout Section
The Solow Model - Continued
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 function is above the 45-degree line, the economy grows.
 When it lies below - the economy declines.
 Anyway, eventually the economy converges to the steady state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A steady state is an equilibrium, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}=\phi(\bar{k})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation has 2 solutions.
 One of them is 0 (the trivial / unstable / unimportant) steady state, the
 other one is non-trivial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of the steady state
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Existence: a steady state might not exist at all, in case the economy diverges
 (e.g infinite growth).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Uniqueness: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 crosses the 45-degree line more than once, the steady state might not be
 unique.
 We know that it is not the case, as the function is concave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stability: the equilibrium might be unstable, depending on the slope of
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 function.
 The oscillations might leads to convergence/divergence.
 The process will be monotonic/oscillatory, depending on whether the slope
 is positive.
 For the Solow model, the monotonic convergence case is the relevant one.
\end_layout

