\begin_layout Section
Overlapping Generations Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic idea is an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extension
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or alternative to the Solow model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Solow model there is no optimization, and the savings rate is a parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model we consider individuals and decisions they make.
 It is a discrete time model, with a generation in each time period.
 The old people retire / die / quit the market, and a new generation takes
 place.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Overlapping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - because in each point in time there are 2 generations alive: the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

young
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main reason people save is for retirement, and the overlapping generations
 model is based on that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production function is similar to that in the Solow model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=F(K_{t},L_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with diminishing marginal product, and constant return to scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Being a competitive model economy, prices are needed.
 The wage per worker is 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}=f(k_{t})-f'(k_{t})k_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, each worker produces 
\begin_inset Formula $f(k_{t})$
\end_inset

 but needs to pay for the capital, as it doesn't belong him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The adults have only wage income, and when they are old they become owners
 and rent the capital.
 The return is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}=f'(k_{t})+1-\delta
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(the value of the capital, net of depreciation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplify the model, no population growth is assumed.
 A generation is born every period and lives for 2 periods.
 There is no decision on how much labor to supply, but individuals do have
 choice on how much to consume/save.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preferences of the individuals are represented by a utility function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}=u(c_{t}^{y},c_{t+1}^{o})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(consumption in young and old age).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The budget constraint is that consumption in the second period is the savings
 + return:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{t+1}^{0}=R_{t+1}s_{t}^{y}=R_{t+1}[w_{1}-c_{t}^{y}]\Rightarrow c_{t}^{y}+\frac{c_{t+1}^{0}}{R_{t+1}}=w_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The saving is the function of the wage and return to capital:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{t}^{y}=s(w_{t},R_{t+1})
\]

\end_inset

Unlike the Solow model, here 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 represents the saving itself (not the fraction).
 As aggregate consumption is a normal good:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{ds_{t}}{dw_{t}}>0;\,\,\frac{ds_{t}}{dR_{t+1}}\geq0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Actually, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ds_{t}}{dw_{t}}<1$
\end_inset

 (otherwise an increase in wage would reduce current consumption).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second assumption is not obvious, as it depends on the income effect
 (more income - consume today) vs.
 substitution effect (incentive to save more).
 The economic theory doesn't predict which one is stronger, thus some assumption
 is to be made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals has a utility function.
 They try to maximize it subject to the budget constraint, which results
 in a decision regarding the savings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The evolution of capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{t+1}=Ls_{t}^{y}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capital in the next period is the savings from the current period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The depreciation is not there, because it has a very limited effect (unlike
 the Solow model) - the capital is consumed by the old generation each period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t+1}=\phi(k_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The dynamical system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the Solow model, here 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily concave, but can be convex as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible that when income is low, people save less (compared to higher
 income, when they save a higher portion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An infinite growth is not possible, as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(k_{t})=s_{t}\leq w_{t}\leq f(k_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People cannot save more than their wage, and the wage cannot be more than
 the output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregate saving in the economy is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}=s_{t}^{y}=s_{t}^{o}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}^{o}=-(1-\delta)k_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}^{y}=k_{t+1}$
\end_inset

.
 The old consume the income and the capital, net of depreciation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the steady state:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{t}=k_{t+1}-(1-\delta)k_{t}\Rightarrow s_{t}=\delta k
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
meaning 
\series bold
saving equals deprecciation
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cobb-Douglas production function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $F(K_{t},L_{t})=AK_{t}^{\alpha}L_{t}^{1-\alpha}=L_{t}Ak_{t}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 the utility is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}=u(c_{t},c_{t+1})=ln(c_{t})+\frac{1}{1+\rho}ln(c_{t+1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the future discount rate.
 The optimization is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{t}=\frac{1}{2+\rho}w_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this function, the interest rate, although affects the resulting total
 capital - doesn't change the savings rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the general case, multiple steady state equilibria are possible.
\end_layout

